import{a as e}from"./chunk-BICP2NS5.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var t={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'Dropbox is a **file hosting + sync** service: a file saved on one device appears on all the others within seconds, works **offline**, supports **sharing** and **version history**, and scales to **hundreds of millions of users** storing **exabytes** of data. The magic is not "store a file in the cloud" \u2014 it is **syncing efficiently**: moving only the bytes that changed, deduplicating identical content, and keeping many devices consistent.'},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"The big idea",body:'Split a file into **content-addressed chunks** and separate **two planes**: the **block plane** (immutable chunk bytes in object storage, deduplicated by hash) and the **metadata plane** (which chunks make up which file, versions, permissions). Sync becomes "diff the chunk lists and transfer only the missing chunks" \u2014 that is **delta sync**, and it is what makes Dropbox feel instant.'},{type:"image",src:"assets/diagrams/dropbox-architecture.svg",alt:"Dropbox architecture: client chunks files and uploads to the block service (deduplicated into block storage), commits the chunk list to the metadata service, which notifies other devices via the notification service to poll the sync delta.",caption:"Block plane (chunk bytes, deduplicated) and metadata plane (file\u2192chunk lists, versions), tied together by a notification + sync-cursor mechanism."}]},{id:"functional-requirements",title:"Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"We scope the interview to the storage + sync core."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"In scope",practices:["**Upload / download** files of any size.","**Sync**: a change on one device propagates to all others.","**Offline edits** that reconcile on reconnect.","**Deduplication**: identical content stored once.","**Delta sync**: transfer only changed chunks, not whole files.","**Versioning**: keep file history; restore previous versions.","**Sharing**: share files/folders with permissions."]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Out of scope (state this explicitly)",body:"Real-time collaborative document editing (that is Google Docs / OT-CRDT territory), search inside file contents, the desktop FS-watcher internals, billing, and admin/enterprise controls. Naming the boundary keeps the focus on chunking, sync, and metadata."}]},{id:"non-functional-requirements",title:"Non-Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"prosCons",title:"Prioritizing the qualities",pros:["Extreme durability \u2014 a stored file must never be lost (target 11+ nines).","Fast sync: small changes propagate within seconds.","Bandwidth + storage efficiency (dedup + delta sync).","High availability for upload/download/sync.","Strong consistency of file metadata (version order must be correct)."],cons:["Cross-device sync is near-real-time, not instantaneous.","Listing/search of metadata can be eventually consistent.","A brief conflict window is acceptable (resolved via conflict copies)."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"CAP framing",body:"The **block store** is AP-ish and immutable (content-addressed chunks are trivially consistent). The **metadata** needs **strong consistency** for a single file's version history \u2014 you must agree on the order of versions so devices converge. Cross-user/cross-folder ordering can be looser."}]},{id:"capacity-estimation",title:"Capacity Estimation",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Assume **500M** users, **~50GB** average stored each, files chunked at **4MB**, and a high rate of small edits (documents, photos) plus large uploads (video)."},{type:"metrics",items:[{label:"Users",value:"~500M",hint:"registered"},{label:"Avg storage / user",value:"~50 GB",hint:"incl. versions"},{label:"Total stored",value:"~25 EB",hint:"before dedup"},{label:"Chunk size",value:"~4 MB",hint:"content-defined"},{label:"Dedup savings",value:"~25\u201350%",hint:"shared/duplicate content"},{label:"Metadata entries",value:"~100s of B",hint:"file\u2192chunk maps"}]},{type:"markdown",value:"The headline insight is that **most uploads are redundant**. A one-line edit to a 50MB document, or re-uploading a file that another user already has, should move almost no bytes. Quantifying delta-sync savings for a small edit:"},{type:"math",display:!0,tex:"Bytes_{sync} = Chunks_{changed} \\times Size_{chunk} \\ll Size_{file} \\quad\\text{e.g. } 1 \\times 4\\,\\text{MB} \\text{ vs a } 500\\,\\text{MB file} = 99.2\\%\\ \\text{saved}",caption:"Delta sync moves only changed chunks. Editing one chunk of a large file transfers kilobytes-to-megabytes, not the whole file."},{type:"markdown",value:"So the engineering effort goes into **chunking, hashing, and dedup** (to minimize bytes stored and moved) and **metadata + notification** (to keep devices in sync), not into raw storage capacity alone."}]},{id:"high-level-architecture",title:"High-Level Architecture",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'The client **watches** the local folder, **chunks** changed files, hashes each chunk, and asks the **Block Service** which chunks are missing (dedup). It uploads only those to **Block Storage**, then **commits** the new file\u2192chunk mapping to the **Metadata Service**. The **Notification Service** tells other devices "something changed"; they pull the **sync delta** and download only the chunks they lack.'},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Block plane, metadata plane, and the notify + sync-delta loop.",definition:`flowchart TD
  ClientA["Client A (watcher + chunker)"] -->|missing? + upload| Block["Block Service"]
  Block --> Dedup{"hash exists?"}
  Dedup -->|no| Store[("Block Storage: S3")]
  Dedup -->|yes| Skip["skip (dedup)"]
  ClientA -->|commit chunk list| Meta["Metadata Service"]
  Meta --> MetaDB[("Metadata DB: MySQL (sharded)")]
  Meta --> Notify["Notification Service"]
  Notify -->|"changed"| ClientB["Client B"]
  ClientB -->|GET delta since cursor| Sync["Sync Service"]
  Sync --> MetaDB
  ClientB -->|download missing chunks| Store`},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Block Service",description:"Receives chunks, computes/validates content hashes, deduplicates (store a chunk only if its hash is new), and writes immutable blocks to object storage. Returns which chunks the client still needs to upload.",icon:"cube",tags:["chunks","dedup","immutable"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Metadata Service",description:"The source of truth for the namespace: which chunks compose each file, version history, directory tree, permissions. Strongly consistent per file; sharded by user/namespace. Drives sync deltas.",icon:"database",tags:["metadata","versions","consistent"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Notification Service",description:'Lightweight long-poll / push channel that tells idle clients "your namespace changed" so they pull a delta. Keeps sync near-real-time without clients constantly polling metadata.',icon:"bell",tags:["long-poll","push","near-real-time"]}]},{id:"chunking-dedup",title:"Chunking & Deduplication",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Files are split into chunks, each identified by the **hash of its content** (content addressing). Two identical chunks \u2014 whether in the same file, across a user's files, or across *different users* \u2014 hash to the same key and are stored **once**. This is the foundation of both dedup and delta sync."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Fixed-size vs content-defined chunking.",columns:["Fixed-size","Content-defined (CDC)"],rows:[{feature:"Simple to implement",values:[!0,!1]},{feature:"Robust to inserts/shifts",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Dedup after a prepend",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Variable chunk boundaries",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Compute cost",values:["Low","Higher (rolling hash)"]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Why content-defined chunking",body:"With fixed 4MB blocks, inserting one byte at the start shifts every boundary, so *every* chunk hash changes \u2014 no dedup. **Content-defined chunking** (a rolling hash like Rabin fingerprinting picks boundaries based on content) keeps boundaries stable across inserts, so an edit only changes the chunks it actually touches."},{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"chunk_and_dedup.py",highlightLines:[4,8,9],code:`def upload(file, block_client):
    chunks = content_defined_chunks(file)        # rolling-hash boundaries
    manifest = []
    hashes = [sha256(c) for c in chunks]          # content address each chunk
    # One round-trip: ask which hashes the server is missing (dedup).
    missing = block_client.which_missing(hashes)
    for c, h in zip(chunks, hashes):
        if h in missing:
            block_client.put(h, c)                # upload only new chunks
        manifest.append(h)
    return manifest                               # file = ordered list of hashes`},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Client-side vs cross-user dedup",body:'Cross-user dedup saves the most storage but has a subtle **security risk**: an attacker could probe whether a chunk already exists to learn someone else has a file. Mitigations include per-user dedup, or requiring proof-of-possession of the full chunk before granting a dedup "skip".'}]},{id:"delta-sync",title:"Delta Sync",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Because a file is an **ordered list of chunk hashes**, syncing a change is just diffing two manifests. The client computes the new manifest, the server compares it to the stored one, and only the **new chunk hashes** are transferred. Editing one paragraph of a huge document moves a single chunk."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Editing one chunk transfers only that chunk.",definition:`flowchart LR
  Old["old manifest: [h1,h2,h3,h4]"] --> Diff{"diff"}
  New["new manifest: [h1,h2,h3',h4]"] --> Diff
  Diff -->|only h3' is new| Up["upload h3' only"]
  Up --> Commit["commit new manifest (version++)"]`},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Sync best practices",practices:["**Manifest = ordered chunk hashes**, so diffing files is trivial.",'**Per-device sync cursor**: "give me everything changed since cursor X" for incremental catch-up.','**Notify, then pull**: a tiny "changed" signal triggers a delta fetch (no constant polling).',"**Compress chunks** before transfer and at rest.","**Batch small files** to avoid per-file round-trip overhead."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"The sync cursor",body:`Each device stores a **cursor** (a logical position in the namespace's change log). On reconnect it asks "what changed since my cursor?" and gets a compact delta. This makes catching up after being offline cheap and resumable.`}]},{id:"api-design",title:"API Design",blocks:[{type:"apiTable",title:"Core endpoints",endpoints:[{method:"POST",path:"/v1/blocks/missing",description:"Given chunk hashes, return which are missing (dedup)",auth:!0},{method:"PUT",path:"/v1/blocks/{hash}",description:"Upload a single chunk",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/blocks/{hash}",description:"Download a chunk",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/files/commit",description:"Commit a file = ordered chunk hashes (new version)",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/delta?cursor=",description:"Changes since cursor (incremental sync)",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/notifications/poll",description:'Long-poll: "namespace changed"',auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/files/{id}/share",description:"Share with permissions",auth:!0}]},{type:"markdown",value:"Commit is **optimistic-concurrency** controlled: the client sends the base version it edited; if the server has moved on, it rejects and the client reconciles (possibly creating a conflict copy)."},{type:"code",language:"json",filename:"commit-file.json",highlightLines:[3,4],code:`{
  "path": "/Work/report.docx",
  "baseVersion": 17,                  // optimistic concurrency check
  "blocks": ["a1f9...", "b2c8...", "c3d7'..."],   // ordered chunk hashes
  "size": 5242880,
  "modified": 1735689600000,
  "deviceId": "dev_a1"
}`}]},{id:"database-design",title:"Database Design",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Two distinct stores: **block storage** (object store, keyed by content hash) and the **metadata DB** (relational, the namespace + versions). Splitting them lets each scale and be optimized independently."},{type:"code",language:"sql",filename:"metadata.sql",highlightLines:[3,11,12],code:`-- Files: current state of each path within a user's namespace.
CREATE TABLE files (
  file_id     BIGINT PRIMARY KEY,
  namespace_id BIGINT NOT NULL,     -- shard key (user or shared folder)
  path        TEXT NOT NULL,
  latest_version BIGINT NOT NULL,
  is_deleted  BOOLEAN DEFAULT false,
  UNIQUE (namespace_id, path)
);
-- Versions: immutable history; a version = ordered list of chunk hashes.
CREATE TABLE file_versions (
  file_id     BIGINT,
  version     BIGINT,               -- monotonic per file
  block_list  JSONB NOT NULL,       -- ["a1f9...", "b2c8...", ...]
  size        BIGINT,
  created_at  TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT now(),
  PRIMARY KEY (file_id, version)
);
-- Blocks: reference count for garbage collection (dedup-aware).
CREATE TABLE blocks (hash TEXT PRIMARY KEY, size INT, refcount BIGINT);`},{type:"table",caption:"Data store chosen per workload.",headers:["Data","Store","Why"],rows:[["Chunk bytes","Object store (S3)","Immutable, content-addressed, durable"],["File / version metadata","Sharded MySQL","Strong consistency, relational, versions"],["Namespace / sharing","MySQL","ACL + directory tree"],["Sync cursors / sessions","Redis","Fast, per-device state"],["Change events","Kafka","Drive notifications + indexing"],["Hot metadata cache","Redis / Memcached","Reduce metadata DB load"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Garbage collection via refcounts",body:"Because chunks are deduplicated and shared, you cannot delete a chunk when one file referencing it is removed. Maintain a **reference count** per block; a background GC reclaims blocks only when their refcount hits zero \u2014 carefully, to avoid races with concurrent uploads."}]},{id:"conflict-resolution",title:"Conflict Resolution",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Two devices edit the same file while offline, then both sync. Unlike a collaborative text editor, Dropbox treats files as opaque blobs, so it cannot merge contents. Instead it uses **optimistic concurrency** on the version number and, on conflict, **keeps both** versions as **conflicted copies** \u2014 never silently losing a user's work."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Concurrent offline edits \u2192 conflicted copy.",definition:`sequenceDiagram
  participant A as Device A
  participant S as Metadata Svc
  participant B as Device B
  A->>S: commit base v17 \u2192 v18 (ok)
  B->>S: commit base v17 \u2192 v18 (CONFLICT: already v18)
  S-->>B: rejected (stale base)
  B->>S: create "report (Device B's conflicted copy).docx"
  S-->>A: notify: new file appeared
  S-->>B: notify: original is now v18`},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Never lose data",body:"The guiding principle: when in doubt, **keep both versions**. A conflicted copy is annoying but recoverable; silently overwriting someone's edit is not. Version history provides an additional safety net to restore any prior state."}]},{id:"communication-flow",title:"Communication Flow",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Editing a file on one device and it appearing on another:"},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Edit \u2192 dedup upload \u2192 commit \u2192 notify \u2192 delta pull.",definition:`sequenceDiagram
  participant A as Device A
  participant Bk as Block Svc
  participant M as Metadata Svc
  participant N as Notification Svc
  participant B as Device B
  A->>A: detect change, chunk + hash
  A->>Bk: which chunks missing?
  Bk-->>A: [h3']
  A->>Bk: upload h3' only
  A->>M: commit manifest (base v17 \u2192 v18)
  M->>N: namespace changed
  N-->>B: "changed" (long-poll returns)
  B->>M: GET delta since cursor
  M-->>B: file report.docx now v18: [h1,h2,h3',h4]
  B->>Bk: download h3' (others already cached)
  B->>B: reassemble + write to disk`},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Most chunks are already local",body:"Device B usually already has h1, h2, h4 from the previous version, so it only fetches the one changed chunk. Reassembly is local. This is why a tiny edit syncs almost instantly."}]},{id:"caching-strategy",title:"Caching Strategy",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Caching spans the client and server. Clients keep a **local chunk cache** so unchanged chunks never re-download. Servers cache **hot metadata** (directory listings, file\u2192manifest maps) and use a **CDN** for frequently downloaded public/shared content."},{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"BlockService.java",highlightLines:[6,7,8],code:`@Service
public class BlockService {
  private final ObjectStore store;     // immutable content-addressed blocks
  private final RefCounts refs;

  public List<String> whichMissing(List<String> hashes) {
    // Dedup check: a chunk we already have never needs re-upload.
    return hashes.stream().filter(h -> !store.exists(h)).toList();
  }

  public void put(String hash, byte[] data) {
    if (!sha256(data).equals(hash)) throw new BadHash();  // integrity
    store.putIfAbsent(hash, data);
    refs.increment(hash);
  }
}`},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Caching best practices applied here",practices:["**Local chunk cache** on each device for instant reassembly + offline access.","**Cache metadata** (listings, manifests) to spare the metadata DB.","**CDN** for hot shared/public downloads.","**Content-addressed = perfectly cacheable**: a hash never maps to different bytes.","**Negative-cache** missing-block checks briefly to speed bulk uploads."]}]},{id:"scaling-strategy",title:"Scaling Strategy",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Separate block from metadata** so each scales on its own axis (bytes vs ops).","**Deduplicate + delta-sync** to slash both storage and bandwidth.","**Shard metadata by namespace** (user / shared folder) for balanced load.","**Notify-then-pull** so idle clients cost almost nothing.","**Offload bytes to object storage + CDN**; app servers handle metadata.","**Async pipelines** (Kafka) for indexing, thumbnails, notifications."]},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Metadata ops dominate, not bytes",body:"Object storage handles the raw bytes effortlessly. The scaling pressure is on **metadata operations** (commits, deltas, listings) and the **notification fan-out** to millions of connected devices \u2014 so those tiers get the most sharding and caching attention."}]},{id:"consistency",title:"Consistency",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A single file's **version history must be strongly consistent** \u2014 devices have to agree on the order of versions to converge. Chunks are immutable and content-addressed, so they are trivially consistent. Cross-namespace listing and notifications can be eventually consistent."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Consistency expectations by data type.",columns:["Strong","Eventual"],rows:[{feature:"Per-file version ordering",values:[!0,!1]},{feature:"Chunk content (immutable)",values:[!0,!1]},{feature:"Cross-folder change listing",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Notification delivery",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Sharing/ACL propagation",values:[!1,!0]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Monotonic versions",body:"Per-file versions increase monotonically and commits use optimistic concurrency on the base version. This gives a clean linear history per file without a global lock, and lets every device deterministically reach the same latest state."}]},{id:"availability",title:"Availability",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The local client is the ultimate availability backstop: files are on disk, so you can read/edit them **fully offline** and sync later. Server-side, block storage and metadata replicate across AZs; if notifications lag, clients still catch up via the sync cursor on the next poll."},{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Graceful degradation",body:"Offline-first design means a server hiccup rarely blocks the user \u2014 edits queue locally and reconcile on reconnect. Never lose a file or a version; conflicts become copies, not data loss."},{type:"youtube",videoId:"U0xTu6E2CT8",title:"Designing a file sync / Dropbox system (illustrative embed)"}]},{id:"partitioning",title:"Partitioning",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Metadata partitions by **namespace** (a user's root, or a shared folder), keeping all of a user's files + versions co-located for fast listing and delta computation. Blocks partition by **content hash** prefix across object storage, spreading bytes uniformly."},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Avoid hot partitions",body:"A huge shared folder (e.g. a team with thousands of members) is a hot namespace: every member's change touches it and notifies everyone. Mitigate by caching the shared namespace's manifest, batching notifications, and sub-partitioning very large shared folders."}]},{id:"sharding",title:"Sharding",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The metadata MySQL tier shards by namespace id (often via a Vitess-like layer) so a single logical schema spans many database nodes. Object storage shards blocks by hash automatically. A routing/lookup layer maps a namespace to its metadata shard."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Namespace-sharded metadata; hash-sharded blocks.",definition:`flowchart LR
  Router["Namespace router"] --> M1["Meta shard 1"]
  Router --> M2["Meta shard 2"]
  Hash["hash(chunk)"] --> B1[("Block bucket A")]
  Hash --> B2[("Block bucket B")]`}]},{id:"replication",title:"Replication",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Object storage replicates each block across zones/regions (erasure coding for cost-efficient durability), targeting 11+ nines. The metadata DB runs primary + synchronous replicas across AZs with quorum so a committed version survives node loss. Cross-region copies provide disaster recovery."},{type:"prosCons",title:"Erasure coding vs full replication (for blocks)",pros:["Much lower storage overhead for the same durability.","Survives multiple simultaneous disk/node failures.","Ideal for large, immutable, cold-ish chunks."],cons:["Higher CPU + latency to reconstruct on read of a lost shard.","More complex than simple N-way replication.","Repair traffic on failures."]}]},{id:"fault-tolerance",title:"Fault Tolerance",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Verify chunk hashes** on upload + download to detect corruption (content addressing makes this free).","**Commit metadata after blocks are durable** so a manifest never references a missing chunk.","**Optimistic concurrency + conflict copies** so concurrent edits never lose data.","**Resumable uploads** so large files survive flaky networks.","**Refcount-aware GC** with safeguards against deleting a block mid-upload.","**Reconciliation**: clients re-scan and compare manifests to self-heal drift."]},{type:"expandable",title:"Example: safe commit ordering",blocks:[{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"commit.py",code:`def commit(file_id, base_version, block_hashes):
    # 1) Ensure every referenced block is already durably stored.
    if not blocks.all_exist(block_hashes):
        raise MissingBlocks()                 # client must upload first
    # 2) Optimistic concurrency: only advance if base is still latest.
    with db.transaction():
        cur = db.latest_version(file_id)
        if cur != base_version:
            raise Conflict(cur)               # client makes a conflicted copy
        new_v = cur + 1
        db.insert_version(file_id, new_v, block_hashes)
        db.set_latest(file_id, new_v)
        blocks.incref(block_hashes)
    notify(file_id)                           # only after durable commit
    return new_v`}]}]},{id:"trade-offs",title:"Trade-offs",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"Key decisions and what they cost.",headers:["Decision","Gain","Cost"],rows:[["Content-defined chunking","Dedup survives inserts/shifts","Rolling-hash CPU cost"],["Block / metadata split","Independent scaling","Two systems to keep in sync"],["Cross-user dedup","Big storage savings","Privacy risk \u2192 needs mitigation"],["Conflict copies (not merge)","Never lose data, simple","User must reconcile manually"],["Notify-then-pull","Cheap idle clients","Slight extra round-trip on change"],["Erasure coding","Cheap durable storage","Reconstruction latency on failure"]]}]},{id:"technology-choices",title:"Technology Choices",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A representative slice of the stack and the role each plays:"},{type:"table",headers:["Concern","Technology"],rows:[["Block storage","Object store (S3 / Magic Pocket)"],["Metadata","Sharded MySQL (+ Vitess-like)"],["Sync cursors / cache","Redis / Memcached"],["Notifications","Long-poll / push service"],["Eventing","Apache Kafka"],["Chunking","Content-defined (rolling hash)"],["Service RPC","gRPC"],["Durability","Erasure coding across zones"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Magic Pocket",body:"Dropbox famously migrated off S3 to its own exabyte-scale storage system, **Magic Pocket**, once it was large enough that owning the storage layer (with custom erasure coding on dense hardware) was cheaper than renting it. A reminder that build-vs-buy flips as you scale."},{type:"code",language:"yaml",filename:"metadata-service.deploy.yaml",code:`service: metadata
strategy: rolling
regions: [us-east-1, eu-west-1]
autoscaling:
  metric: commits_per_sec
  target: 3000
  min: 20
  max: 800
healthCheck:
  path: /health
  unhealthyThreshold: 3`}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",items:[{question:"How do you sync only what changed instead of re-uploading whole files?",answer:"Split files into **content-addressed chunks** and represent a file as an ordered list of chunk hashes (a manifest). On edit, diff the new manifest against the old; only **new chunk hashes** are uploaded, and other devices download only the chunks they lack. That is **delta sync** \u2014 a one-line edit moves one chunk."},{question:"Why content-defined chunking instead of fixed-size blocks?",answer:"With fixed blocks, inserting a byte at the start shifts every boundary, changing all chunk hashes and defeating dedup. **Content-defined chunking** uses a rolling hash to pick boundaries based on content, so boundaries stay stable across inserts and only truly-changed chunks differ."},{question:"How does deduplication work and what is the risk?",answer:"Chunks are keyed by content hash, so identical content (within a file, across files, or across users) is stored once. The risk with **cross-user** dedup is an existence oracle (probe whether a chunk exists to learn someone has a file); mitigate with per-user dedup or proof-of-possession before allowing a dedup skip."},{question:"How do you handle two devices editing the same file offline?",answer:"Use **optimistic concurrency** on the file version. The first commit wins; the second has a stale base version and is rejected, so the client creates a **conflicted copy** instead of overwriting. The principle is never lose data \u2014 keep both, plus version history as a safety net."},{question:"How do other devices learn about a change quickly?",answer:'A lightweight **notification service** (long-poll/push) tells idle clients "your namespace changed". They then pull a **delta since their sync cursor** and download only missing chunks. Notify-then-pull keeps sync near-real-time without constant polling.'},{question:"How do you delete chunks safely with dedup?",answer:"Maintain a **reference count** per block. Removing a file decrements refcounts; a background GC reclaims a block only when its refcount reaches zero, with safeguards against races with concurrent uploads that might re-reference it."}]}]},{id:"references",title:"References",blocks:[{type:"references",items:[{label:"Inside the Magic Pocket (Dropbox storage)",url:"https://dropbox.tech/infrastructure/inside-the-magic-pocket",source:"Dropbox"},{label:"Streaming File Synchronization (rsync / delta)",url:"https://rsync.samba.org/tech_report/",source:"rsync"},{label:"Content-Defined Chunking & Rabin Fingerprinting",url:"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolling_hash",source:"Wikipedia"},{label:"Scaling Dropbox's Edge Network",url:"https://dropbox.tech/infrastructure",source:"Dropbox"},{label:"Erasure Coding for Durable Storage",url:"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erasure_code",source:"Wikipedia"}]}]},{id:"summary",title:"Summary",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Key takeaways",body:`1. **Chunk files into content-addressed blocks** and split the **block plane** (immutable bytes, deduplicated) from the **metadata plane** (file\u2192chunk manifests, versions).
2. **Delta sync**: a file is an ordered list of chunk hashes, so syncing transfers only the chunks that changed.
3. **Content-defined chunking** keeps dedup effective across inserts/shifts.
4. **Never lose data**: optimistic concurrency + conflicted copies + version history; refcount-based GC for shared chunks.
5. **Notify-then-pull** with per-device sync cursors keeps many devices consistent cheaply; metadata ops + notification fan-out are the real scaling pressure, not raw bytes.`}]}]},i=t;export{i as default};
